PHS Scottish Stroke Statistics

This notebook contains analysis steps of stroke incidence and mortality data across Scotland.

  • Raw datasets are from PHS open data accessible via: https://www.opendata.nhs.scot/dataset/scottish-stroke-statistics
  • The raw datasets have been cleaned and saved within the folder ../clean_data/ the cleaned datafiles will be used and analysed here.

2. General exploration data contents

Initially we focus on Health boards as data contents are similar except for area.

# general exploration mortality
# most categories for character data are similar for activity and mortality datasets, except:

mortality_hb %>% 
  distinct(diagnosis)
# 3 diagnosis types: Cerebrovascular disease, stroke, Subarachnoid haemorrhage

crude rate and easr Two columns in all PHS open data files are of interest for data visualisation:

crude rate: The crude rate is the population-standardised rate of the event (here: incidences or moratlity rate) Crude rate is the number of events per 100.000 people

EASR: is the The European Age-Sex Standardised Rate per 100,000 population. The numbers of deaths per 100 000 population are influenced by the age distribution of the population. use is made of the European Standard Population (ESP) to age and sex standardise.

Visualisations - are organised per data file / topic

3a = stroke activity per HB 3b = stroke mortality per HB 3c = mortality per simd (Scottish Index Multiple Deprivation) 4a = stroke activity per HB - demographics 4b = stroke activity per HB - demographics

3A. General insights Stroke activity per HB

What is the number of total stroke incidences in Scotland per year from 2012 to now?

Data/graph shows the total number of stroke incidences in Scotland over the years 2012/13 - 2021/22. We see an initial increase until 2016 after incidence rates are more stable.

However this gives the absolute number of incidences, which are not standardised for age and sex composition differences in the population across years. The population size changes and you want to standardise for this.

age-sex standardised stroke incidences in Scotland per year

What is the number of total stroke incidences split per diagnosis type?

activity_hb %>% 
  select(financial_year, hbr, age_group, sex, admission_type, diagnosis, number_of_discharges, crude_rate, easr) %>% 
  filter(age_group == "All",
         admission_type == "All",
         sex == "All",
         hbr == "S92000003") %>% 
  group_by(financial_year, diagnosis) %>% 
  summarise(total_incidences_easr = sum(easr)) %>% 
  ggplot() +
  aes(x = financial_year, y = total_incidences_easr, fill = diagnosis) +
  geom_col(position = "dodge")

`summarise()` has grouped output by 'financial_year'. You can override using the `.groups` argument.

Graph shows the total number of stroke incidences in Scotland over the years 2012/13 - 2021/22 divided for diagnosis type. Majority of cases are diagnosed as Cerebrovascular disease, followed by Stroke. Small number of cases are diagnosed as TIA, followed by Subarachnoid Haemorrhage. We see an initial increase until 2016 after incidence rates are more stable. Largest differences are found in Cerebrovascular disease and Stroke, while TIA and Subarachnoid Haemorrhage are relatively stable across all years.

What is the number of total stroke incidences split per admission type?

activity_hb %>% 
  select(financial_year, hbr, age_group, sex, admission_type, diagnosis, number_of_discharges, crude_rate, easr) %>% 
  filter(age_group == "All",
         admission_type != "All",
         sex == "All",
         hbr == "S92000003") %>% 
  group_by(financial_year, admission_type) %>% 
  summarise(total_incidences_easr = sum(easr)) %>% 
  ggplot() +
  aes(x = financial_year, y = total_incidences_easr, fill = admission_type) +
  geom_col(position = "dodge")

`summarise()` has grouped output by 'financial_year'. You can override using the `.groups` argument.

Graph shows the total number of stroke incidences in Scotland over the years 2012/13 - 2021/22 split for admission type. Largest number of incidences are transfered patients, followed by emergency cases. A small minority of admitted incidences are elective.

3B. General insights Stroke mortality per hb

What is the stroke mortality rate in Scotland per year?

Graph shows the total number of deaths due to strokes in Scotland over the year 2012-2021. Total number of deaths has decreased over the years comparing start to end year, with a reduction of ~1000 cases

However this gives the absolute number of deaths, which are not standardised for age and sex composition differences in the population across years. The population size changes and you want to standardise for this.

age-sex standardised stroke deaths in Scotland per year

What is the number of deaths split per diagnosis type?

mortality_hb %>% 
  select(year, hbr, age_group, sex, diagnosis, number_of_deaths, easr) %>% 
  filter(age_group == "All",
         sex == "All",
         hbr == "S92000003") %>% 
  group_by(year, diagnosis) %>% 
  summarise(total_deaths_easr = sum(easr)) %>% 
  ggplot() +
  aes(x = year, y = total_deaths_easr, fill = diagnosis) +
  geom_col(position = "dodge")

`summarise()` has grouped output by 'year'. You can override using the `.groups` argument.

Graph shows the total number of deaths due to strokes in Scotland over the year 2012-2021 split by diagnosis type. Majority of deaths are diagnosed as Cerebrovascular disease, followed by stroke. Only a minority is caused by Subarachnoid haemorrhage.

3C. Stroke mortality per SIMD

Visualise the number of deaths (use age-sex standardised rate per 100k population)

Graph shows the age-sex standardised mortality rates (per 100,000 people) per SIMD quintile. Indicating that mortality rate for CD is higher in areas of higher deprivation.

4A. Stroke incidence rate - demographics

Visualise the number of incidences (use age-sex standardised rate per 100k population) split per age-group and sex

sex

activity_hb %>% 
  select(financial_year, hbr, age_group, sex, admission_type, diagnosis, number_of_discharges, crude_rate, easr) %>% 
  filter(age_group == "All",
         admission_type == "All",
         sex == "Males" | sex == "Females",
         hbr == "S92000003") %>% 
  group_by(financial_year, sex) %>% 
  summarise(total_incidences_easr = sum(easr)) %>% 
  ggplot() +
  aes(x = financial_year, y = total_incidences_easr) +
  geom_line(aes(group = sex, colour = sex), size = 2) +
  theme_light() +
  labs(
    x = "\nYear", 
    y = "age-sex adjusted incidence rate per 100,000 population",
    title = "Cerebrovascular Disease Standardised Incidences per Year per Sex",
    subtitle = "age and sex adjusted incidence rates per year (ESP-2013)"
  ) +
  scale_y_continuous(limits = c(0, 1500)) +
  scale_colour_manual(
    values = c(
      "Males" = "palegreen4",
      "Females" = "palegreen1")
    )

`summarise()` has grouped output by 'financial_year'. You can override using the `.groups` argument.

age_group

activity_hb %>% 
  select(financial_year, hbr, age_group, sex, admission_type, diagnosis, number_of_discharges, crude_rate, easr) %>% 
  filter(age_group == "0-44 years" | age_group == "45-64 years" | 
           age_group == "65-74 years" | age_group == "75plus years",
         admission_type == "All",
         sex == "All",
         hbr == "S92000003") %>% 
  group_by(financial_year, age_group) %>% 
  summarise(total_incidences_easr = sum(easr)) %>% 
  ggplot() +
  aes(x = financial_year, y = total_incidences_easr) +
  geom_line(aes(group = age_group, colour = age_group), size = 1.5) +
  theme_light() +
  labs(
    x = "\nYear", 
    y = "age-sex adjusted incidence rate per 100,000 population",
    title = "Cerebrovascular Disease Standardised Incidences per Age-group",
    subtitle = "age and sex adjusted incidence rates per year (ESP-2013)",
    colour = "Age group"
  ) +
  scale_y_continuous(limits = c(0, 8000)) +
  scale_colour_manual(
    values = c(
      "0-44 years" = "palegreen4",
      "45-64 years" = "palegreen3",
      "65-74 years" = "palegreen1",
      "75plus years" = "limegreen")
    )

`summarise()` has grouped output by 'financial_year'. You can override using the `.groups` argument.

4B. Stroke mortality rate - demographics

Visualise the number of deaths (use age-sex standardised rate per 100k population) split per age-group and sex

sex

mortality_hb %>% 
  select(year, hbr, age_group, sex, diagnosis, number_of_deaths, easr, crude_rate) %>% 
  filter(age_group == "All",
         sex == "Males" | sex == "Females",
         hbr == "S92000003") %>% 
  group_by(year, sex) %>% 
  summarise(total_deaths_easr = sum(easr)) %>% 
  ggplot() +
  aes(x = as.factor(year), y = total_deaths_easr) +

  theme_light() +
  labs(
    x = "\nYear", 
    y = "age-sex adjusted death rate per 100,000 population",

    subtitle = "age and sex adjusted death rates per year (ESP-2013)"
  ) +
  scale_y_continuous(limits = c(0, 400)) +
  scale_colour_manual(
    values = c(
      "Males" = "palegreen4",
